WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-US

00:00:05.095 --> 00:00:09.649
<v Mike Demopoulos> Hello and
welcome to the 2 o'clock hour UTC

00:00:09.674 --> 00:00:13.189
of WP Accessibility Day 2020.

00:00:13.214 --> 00:00:18.184
I'm your host, Mike Demo, and I am so
excited about today: the next presentation.

00:00:18.217 --> 00:00:21.014
But before we get to that,
a little bit of housekeeping.

00:00:21.039 --> 00:00:23.472
First of all, remember that
we are a welcoming community,

00:00:23.497 --> 00:00:27.544
and the code of conduct is enforced
in all areas of the experience,

00:00:27.569 --> 00:00:28.899
including the chat.

00:00:28.924 --> 00:00:31.774
And that chat's important because
that's where you put the questions,

00:00:31.799 --> 00:00:34.100
and our wonderful moderators
will click them

00:00:34.133 --> 00:00:36.983
for me to ask after the presentation.

00:00:37.008 --> 00:00:41.008
Please make sure to follow us
on Twitter @WPAccessibility,

00:00:41.033 --> 00:00:45.878
and our two hashtags are
#wpaccessibilityday

00:00:45.903 --> 00:00:49.782
and #wpad2020.

00:00:51.063 --> 00:00:53.773
Up next, we have
Christina Workman.

00:00:53.798 --> 00:00:59.384
Christina Workman is a support technician
at WebDevStudios and Maintainn.

00:00:59.409 --> 00:01:01.765
As an advocate for
contributing to WordPress,

00:01:01.790 --> 00:01:05.089
she recently launched
the wp_contribute() podcast

00:01:05.114 --> 00:01:11.246
and helps organize WordCamp US, WordCamp
Calgary, and the Calgary WordPress Meetup.

00:01:11.271 --> 00:01:15.959
She has a passion for teaching kids STEM
and improving her accessibility skills.

00:01:15.984 --> 00:01:20.237
Outside of WordPress,
Christina is a purple-o-phile,

00:01:20.262 --> 00:01:24.806
tea fanatic, and lover of
British detective shows.

00:01:24.831 --> 00:01:28.588
So, with that, it is my pleasure
to welcome my friend Christina.

00:01:28.950 --> 00:01:30.530
<v Christina Workman> Hi, Mike. Thanks.

00:01:32.129 --> 00:01:34.828
All right, let me just get the slides.

00:01:35.621 --> 00:01:36.778
All right.
Hi, everyone.

00:01:36.803 --> 00:01:39.748
Thanks for joining me for
our accessibility--sorry.

00:01:39.773 --> 00:01:42.275
Accessible Websites Benefit Everyone.

00:01:43.259 --> 00:01:45.415
First, a little bit about me:
I know Mike already

00:01:45.440 --> 00:01:48.027
sort of touched on a lot of these points.

00:01:48.497 --> 00:01:52.265
But I do have a podcast
called wp_contribute(),

00:01:52.336 --> 00:01:55.646
where I interview people who
contribute to the WordPress Project.

00:01:56.289 --> 00:01:59.836
I've been a Meetup and WordCamp
organizer for several years.

00:01:59.861 --> 00:02:03.297
And a good chunk of everything
that I have learned about WordPress,

00:02:03.322 --> 00:02:05.387
I have learned at these kinds of events.

00:02:06.148 --> 00:02:08.306
I've been using WordPress
for about ten years now,

00:02:09.529 --> 00:02:14.287
first as a freelancer and then,
as Mike said, a support technician

00:02:14.312 --> 00:02:17.638
at the Maintainn Division
for WebDevStudios.

00:02:18.392 --> 00:02:23.334
I love tea and have at least a hundred
different kinds of tea in my kitchen.

00:02:23.682 --> 00:02:25.928
And as Mike said,
I'm a purple-o-phile.

00:02:25.962 --> 00:02:28.517
I am obsessed with
all things purple,

00:02:28.542 --> 00:02:31.293
as you can probably tell
from my slides and my shirt,

00:02:31.318 --> 00:02:33.705
and, I don't know if you
see my headphones.

00:02:34.626 --> 00:02:35.713
So yeah.

00:02:35.738 --> 00:02:38.332
I'm still a little bit of
an accessibility newbie;

00:02:39.420 --> 00:02:43.749
maybe about two years ago,
I started to learn about and consider

00:02:43.773 --> 00:02:45.372
accessibility for websites.

00:02:45.896 --> 00:02:48.346
But even in that short time,
I've noticed

00:02:48.989 --> 00:02:53.147
that a lot of people
still have a lot of apprehension

00:02:53.172 --> 00:02:55.560
about making sure
their sites are accessible.

00:02:56.560 --> 00:03:00.639
My goal with this talk
is to help you recognize

00:03:00.664 --> 00:03:04.300
that implementing best practices
to make your website accessible

00:03:04.325 --> 00:03:08.739
will ensure a better user experience
for all of your site visitors.

00:03:09.228 --> 00:03:11.407
I'll be discussing
various examples.

00:03:12.066 --> 00:03:14.034
They are by no means exhaustive,

00:03:15.177 --> 00:03:20.401
and I hope that you will start thinking of
your own examples as we go through these

00:03:20.426 --> 00:03:22.365
and once everything is done.

00:03:24.047 --> 00:03:26.856
So there are lots of reasons
that people give

00:03:26.881 --> 00:03:29.510
about why they won't
make their sites accessible,

00:03:29.535 --> 00:03:32.778
and I'm sure lots of you
have a lot of these already.

00:03:32.811 --> 00:03:36.621
So, the first one, of course,
it costs too much.

00:03:37.264 --> 00:03:39.724
And there are a ton of
counter-arguments to this.

00:03:40.153 --> 00:03:44.383
But essentially, the sooner you start
recognizing and considering accessibility,

00:03:44.408 --> 00:03:45.757
the less it's going to cost.

00:03:46.501 --> 00:03:48.860
Another one is, it
will wreck my design.

00:03:50.344 --> 00:03:53.515
It might change your design,
but of course, you can still make

00:03:53.540 --> 00:03:56.881
beautiful, creative, and
accessible websites.

00:03:57.818 --> 00:04:01.725
And the third one,
my site visitors don't have disabilities.

00:04:04.122 --> 00:04:06.284
This is a giant fallacy

00:04:06.308 --> 00:04:09.506
which often goes hand-in-hand
with the misconception

00:04:09.531 --> 00:04:14.126
that accessibility is purely
for the sake of people with disabilities,

00:04:14.814 --> 00:04:17.345
and for some, maybe to avoid lawsuits,

00:04:17.370 --> 00:04:19.770
just not the right reason to be doing it.

00:04:20.849 --> 00:04:22.631
Not only do I guarantee, though,

00:04:22.655 --> 00:04:26.371
that your site has visitors
who have disabilities,

00:04:26.848 --> 00:04:29.226
I also know that an accessible website

00:04:29.251 --> 00:04:32.648
can have a positive impact
on anyone who visits that site.

00:04:33.397 --> 00:04:35.337
We need to start understanding

00:04:35.362 --> 00:04:41.234
that an accessible website is one
that can easily be used by everyone.

00:04:43.649 --> 00:04:47.125
So you might be thinking,
how can I be so sure

00:04:47.150 --> 00:04:50.769
that your site
has visitors with disabilities?

00:04:51.192 --> 00:04:52.506
The answer is simple.

00:04:53.132 --> 00:04:56.069
We have all experienced disability,

00:04:56.554 --> 00:05:00.442
some form of disability in our lives,
and we will again.

00:05:01.359 --> 00:05:06.549
Often, the image of a person with
a disability is somebody who is blind

00:05:06.574 --> 00:05:10.444
or deaf or has lost the use of a limb.

00:05:12.146 --> 00:05:15.431
These are considered
permanent disabilities,

00:05:15.465 --> 00:05:20.036
but there are also temporary
and situational disabilities.

00:05:20.747 --> 00:05:22.560
So to put these into context,

00:05:24.670 --> 00:05:27.042
if you have an amputated arm,

00:05:27.067 --> 00:05:29.685
that, of course, would be
a permanent disability.

00:05:30.232 --> 00:05:34.235
But a broken arm, which
would be a temporary disability,

00:05:34.260 --> 00:05:37.039
can have the same
impact on how you function.

00:05:38.080 --> 00:05:44.058
And an armful of groceries also prevents
you from using that arm for other purposes

00:05:44.083 --> 00:05:45.840
for a very short period of time.

00:05:46.537 --> 00:05:47.803
That's situational.

00:05:49.038 --> 00:05:51.728
And there are lots of
accessibility considerations

00:05:51.753 --> 00:05:53.357
that make life easier

00:05:53.382 --> 00:05:56.784
for people who aren't experiencing
any form of disability.

00:05:57.948 --> 00:06:00.144
So let's get to some examples.

00:06:00.169 --> 00:06:02.781
And as I said, these are
by no means exhaustive.

00:06:02.806 --> 00:06:05.353
There are a million different examples,

00:06:05.997 --> 00:06:10.558
and we're not going to touch
on every type of disability,

00:06:11.078 --> 00:06:14.147
but I hope these get
you to start thinking.

00:06:15.205 --> 00:06:16.607
So, first scenario.

00:06:17.348 --> 00:06:20.574
You get home from work and
you have to feed your kids.

00:06:20.599 --> 00:06:22.338
You have a migraine.

00:06:22.363 --> 00:06:25.292
The kids are excited and loud,

00:06:25.317 --> 00:06:27.840
which adds to the brain fog
from your migraine.

00:06:28.511 --> 00:06:30.818
You decide to order
delivery from a website.

00:06:32.847 --> 00:06:35.836
So let's discuss
some of the potential barriers

00:06:35.861 --> 00:06:40.309
that could make this a difficult
experience for you in this scenario.

00:06:45.574 --> 00:06:47.399
Confusing navigation.

00:06:47.424 --> 00:06:49.716
Hard-to-find buttons and links.

00:06:50.686 --> 00:06:52.391
These need to be clear

00:06:52.415 --> 00:06:56.006
where you're going to click in
order to get to the ordering portal,

00:06:56.031 --> 00:06:58.006
to add items to your cart,

00:06:58.031 --> 00:06:59.811
to pay for your order,

00:06:59.835 --> 00:07:01.137
all of these kinds of things.

00:07:01.162 --> 00:07:04.532
Otherwise, you'll end up
getting confused and frustrated.

00:07:05.762 --> 00:07:08.963
Too many calls to action
fighting for your attention

00:07:10.013 --> 00:07:13.566
when you can barely think
because of the migraine and brain fog

00:07:13.599 --> 00:07:14.960
that you have going on,

00:07:14.985 --> 00:07:17.491
these are distractions that
are too hard to cope with.

00:07:18.099 --> 00:07:20.083
So again, confusion can ensue.

00:07:21.300 --> 00:07:25.786
Fast-moving animations
similar to too many CTAs,

00:07:25.811 --> 00:07:28.407
but also, these can make
your headache worse

00:07:28.432 --> 00:07:31.862
and make it hard for you
to even look at the screen.

00:07:32.956 --> 00:07:35.522
And finally, some
checkout form issues.

00:07:36.174 --> 00:07:39.658
Input field labels used as placeholder text

00:07:39.683 --> 00:07:42.438
that disappear when you
start typing in that field.

00:07:43.205 --> 00:07:48.021
I've been caught by these when
I'm not giving my site my full attention,

00:07:48.046 --> 00:07:49.422
even without a headache.

00:07:50.783 --> 00:07:55.570
Imagine in our scenario,
you click into a field,

00:07:55.595 --> 00:07:58.844
you hear a crash in the
living room that distracts you,

00:07:58.877 --> 00:08:03.749
and when you return back to that form
and return your attention there,

00:08:03.774 --> 00:08:07.019
you have no recollection
of what that input field was for

00:08:07.052 --> 00:08:08.835
and what you are
supposed to enter there.

00:08:10.026 --> 00:08:13.763
And something I see less often
but certainly has happened,

00:08:14.451 --> 00:08:18.941
the inability to click into a
field can baffle and frustrate

00:08:18.966 --> 00:08:21.647
and make you think that
it's impossible to complete this order.

00:08:23.735 --> 00:08:28.797
All of these factors could result in you
giving up on placing an order on the site

00:08:29.247 --> 00:08:30.975
and taking your business elsewhere.

00:08:31.610 --> 00:08:36.978
Not to mention adding to just
the general frustration and chaos

00:08:37.003 --> 00:08:38.573
that's happening around you.

00:08:39.710 --> 00:08:42.770
Migraines fall under the
neurological category,

00:08:42.795 --> 00:08:46.525
which would include
other things such as ADHD,

00:08:46.558 --> 00:08:50.274
autism, and epilepsy as
permanent disabilities.

00:08:51.191 --> 00:08:54.840
So who else can benefit from
neurological considerations?

00:08:56.807 --> 00:09:00.669
I'm sure you can all relate to
at least one of these situations.

00:09:01.573 --> 00:09:04.446
Brain fog, which can happen on its own

00:09:04.471 --> 00:09:08.802
or can be a result of a
lack of sleep or a flu or cold;

00:09:09.992 --> 00:09:16.555
mental health concerns like anxiety,
depression, even general stress

00:09:16.588 --> 00:09:21.032
can impact your ability to focus
and process what you see on a site

00:09:21.509 --> 00:09:25.215
as well as simply being
in a distracting environment.

00:09:26.608 --> 00:09:30.779
Neurological accessibility
benefits everyone.

00:09:33.222 --> 00:09:34.756
So, our next scenario.

00:09:36.114 --> 00:09:38.848
You decide to remote work
from a local coffee shop.

00:09:39.377 --> 00:09:41.273
I used to do this all the time.

00:09:42.146 --> 00:09:45.483
You get stuck on a problem
and search for a tutorial.

00:09:46.338 --> 00:09:50.730
You find the perfect video
embedded on its own webpage,

00:09:51.215 --> 00:09:53.557
but darn it, you forgot
your headphones at home.

00:09:55.612 --> 00:09:57.656
So what are some
potential complications here?

00:09:59.094 --> 00:10:02.947
First, if there are no closed captions
or subtitling available,

00:10:03.494 --> 00:10:06.693
you can't watch it on mute
and know what's being said.

00:10:07.967 --> 00:10:11.554
If video is the only way the
information was presented,

00:10:11.579 --> 00:10:15.778
there's no transcript or blog post
that sums up that information,

00:10:16.509 --> 00:10:18.877
both of these results
in you being unable

00:10:18.902 --> 00:10:23.566
to get the information that
you need when you need it.

00:10:24.813 --> 00:10:27.381
The last item isn't necessarily a barrier

00:10:27.857 --> 00:10:32.037
but definitely has the potential to
cause issues and embarrassment.

00:10:32.637 --> 00:10:35.404
The video is set to autoplay,

00:10:37.406 --> 00:10:39.043
and as soon as the page loads,

00:10:39.067 --> 00:10:43.018
the audio is streaming out
of your laptop for all to hear.

00:10:43.686 --> 00:10:47.850
Personally, I've actually been
startled by autoplaying videos before,

00:10:47.875 --> 00:10:51.010
even on sites I repeatedly visit.

00:10:52.306 --> 00:10:55.031
These issues are all audio related

00:10:55.065 --> 00:10:58.800
and certainly affect people who have
some form of permanent hearing loss.

00:10:59.470 --> 00:11:02.100
But there are a variety of
other people who can benefit

00:11:02.124 --> 00:11:04.030
from text alternatives to audio,

00:11:05.953 --> 00:11:09.929
people with temporary hearing loss
due to tinnitus

00:11:09.953 --> 00:11:14.629
or a plugged ear that could be caused
from an ear infection or allergies

00:11:14.653 --> 00:11:18.424
or even if you've been traveling
and just got off a plane.

00:11:19.726 --> 00:11:23.615
I often prefer to skim through
text to find a quick answer

00:11:23.648 --> 00:11:25.295
rather than watching a video.

00:11:26.668 --> 00:11:31.112
And some people simply process
information better by reading it

00:11:31.137 --> 00:11:32.601
rather than listening to it.

00:11:33.934 --> 00:11:38.449
People learning a new language
may use subtitles to follow along

00:11:38.474 --> 00:11:41.573
and help them learn and
understand the language better.

00:11:43.025 --> 00:11:46.009
And of course, in this age,
we have digital assistants

00:11:46.034 --> 00:11:48.990
like Siri, Google Assistant, Alexa,

00:11:49.014 --> 00:11:52.129
and they can all read text from websites
if it's there.

00:11:53.129 --> 00:11:55.424
And, of course,
loud environments in general

00:11:55.465 --> 00:11:59.294
can make it very hard to understand
what is being said in audio.

00:12:00.501 --> 00:12:03.971
Audio accessibility benefits everyone.

00:12:05.995 --> 00:12:07.636
So, our third scenario.

00:12:09.327 --> 00:12:13.168
You're a WordPress developer who
never takes their hands off the keyboard.

00:12:14.057 --> 00:12:16.714
You know all the keyboard shortcuts,

00:12:16.739 --> 00:12:20.817
and there's not a mouse to be
found anywhere in your office.

00:12:21.428 --> 00:12:24.595
You decide to register in an online course

00:12:24.620 --> 00:12:27.045
with the latest and
greatest headless platform.

00:12:29.414 --> 00:12:33.395
So let's look at some of the barriers
you might experience with this scenario.

00:12:35.537 --> 00:12:37.392
No "Skip to Content" option,

00:12:38.003 --> 00:12:40.989
which means you have to tab through
every single item in the header

00:12:41.014 --> 00:12:43.376
before getting to the
main part of the page.

00:12:44.344 --> 00:12:49.005
Add to that a main navigation that
forces you to tap through every sub item.

00:12:49.489 --> 00:12:53.092
And you may feel like it's never
going to get off of the header.

00:12:54.338 --> 00:12:55.814
No focus indication

00:12:56.148 --> 00:12:59.493
means you can't see
where you are on that page,

00:12:59.518 --> 00:13:02.390
what link or button you might click
if you hit enter.

00:13:03.692 --> 00:13:06.257
Then we've got unexpected tab behavior,

00:13:06.282 --> 00:13:12.162
which can take you all over the page
in some random experiences.

00:13:12.187 --> 00:13:15.685
And I've seen where it goes
straight from the "Skip to Content"

00:13:15.710 --> 00:13:18.574
right down to the bottom
to the chat box that they have,

00:13:18.599 --> 00:13:21.202
then back up to the top,
and then into the middle,

00:13:24.313 --> 00:13:29.189
and that's just so confusing when you're
trying to follow the flow of the page.

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:34.092
And then, by the time you finally
read the information about the course

00:13:34.117 --> 00:13:35.974
and decide to register,

00:13:35.999 --> 00:13:37.903
you may encounter keyboard traps

00:13:37.928 --> 00:13:40.869
like not being able to
return to a field once it's filled out

00:13:41.603 --> 00:13:45.567
or not being able to leave the
registration form unless you hit submit.

00:13:46.487 --> 00:13:50.012
These are frustrations
that people with physical disabilities,

00:13:50.037 --> 00:13:54.163
who need to use keyboards or other
special devices to navigate websites,

00:13:54.188 --> 00:13:55.389
face all the time.

00:13:56.897 --> 00:13:59.295
So here's some other examples
of when you might need

00:13:59.320 --> 00:14:01.644
or want to rely solely on your keyboard.

00:14:04.136 --> 00:14:07.646
You may have a broken arm, a
broken wrist, a broken finger.

00:14:07.671 --> 00:14:12.284
Anything on that limb that
is just not functioning

00:14:12.317 --> 00:14:15.154
or even if it does function.

00:14:15.179 --> 00:14:17.374
I've had my finger broken before,

00:14:17.399 --> 00:14:19.258
and you get that splint on it.

00:14:19.291 --> 00:14:22.484
And try using a mouse with
a splint on your finger.

00:14:22.509 --> 00:14:23.762
It just doesn't work.

00:14:25.516 --> 00:14:28.037
Maybe you have carpal tunnel
syndrome or something else

00:14:28.062 --> 00:14:31.623
that flares up every now and then,
but not all the time.

00:14:32.814 --> 00:14:35.984
Maybe you have a wireless
mouse, and the battery died

00:14:36.009 --> 00:14:38.302
and you don't have any
extra batteries in the house.

00:14:39.397 --> 00:14:42.953
Or my personal favorite,
you have a sleeping baby or pet

00:14:42.978 --> 00:14:44.020
on your lap.

00:14:44.948 --> 00:14:49.528
My dog loves to sit on my lap
and rest his head on my dominant arm,

00:14:49.553 --> 00:14:51.883
and I hate to disturb him,

00:14:51.907 --> 00:14:53.672
so I don't move my arm.

00:14:53.697 --> 00:14:58.693
I just put it in position on the keyboard
and try to type as best I can

00:14:58.718 --> 00:15:00.250
and use my
other hand as well.

00:15:01.752 --> 00:15:05.189
So keyboard accessibility
benefits everyone.

00:15:08.175 --> 00:15:10.199
Our last scenario.

00:15:10.224 --> 00:15:13.671
You live in Oregon on the
West Coast in the United States,

00:15:13.696 --> 00:15:15.076
and its three weeks ago.

00:15:15.949 --> 00:15:18.996
Temperatures are high and you
don't have an air conditioner,

00:15:19.021 --> 00:15:20.684
so windows need to be open.

00:15:21.374 --> 00:15:24.069
Wildfires break out all around you,

00:15:24.093 --> 00:15:28.812
causing poor air quality that irritates
your eyes and blurs your vision.

00:15:29.685 --> 00:15:34.090
You have to evacuate to a more
rural area that has poor wi-fi,

00:15:34.558 --> 00:15:36.799
and you're going to work
remotely while you're there,

00:15:36.824 --> 00:15:39.870
and you need to visit a variety
of websites throughout the day.

00:15:41.371 --> 00:15:43.084
So let's look at our barriers here.

00:15:44.759 --> 00:15:46.663
When you have blurry eyes,

00:15:46.687 --> 00:15:52.506
trying to read small or skinny
font text is really difficult.

00:15:53.308 --> 00:15:56.588
Low contrast between the
foreground and the background

00:15:56.621 --> 00:15:58.342
can make it hard to see information

00:15:58.367 --> 00:16:01.177
when you're trying to get your
eyes to focus and they won't.

00:16:02.002 --> 00:16:06.335
Linked text can be hard to
notice if it's only using color

00:16:06.360 --> 00:16:08.359
to differentiate from regular text

00:16:08.384 --> 00:16:10.051
and if the colors are too similar.

00:16:11.027 --> 00:16:15.062
Maybe you want to zoom in
to make it easier to read the content,

00:16:15.126 --> 00:16:17.705
but the layout isn't suited to resizing.

00:16:18.141 --> 00:16:22.396
So images and maybe even text
go off the side of the screen,

00:16:22.421 --> 00:16:24.148
and you can't access it.

00:16:24.894 --> 00:16:28.418
And if images don't load
because of the weak Wi-Fi

00:16:28.443 --> 00:16:30.838
and there is no alternative text,

00:16:30.863 --> 00:16:33.686
you could be missing out
on important information.

00:16:34.826 --> 00:16:37.384
These all fall into the visual category,

00:16:37.409 --> 00:16:40.712
affecting people who have
colorblindness or reduced vision.

00:16:41.833 --> 00:16:46.601
And again, we have lots of scenarios that
can affect your ability to see a website.

00:16:48.601 --> 00:16:53.192
You may have an eye injury, maybe
you had eye surgery or an eye infection.

00:16:54.145 --> 00:16:57.175
I heard this mentioned
in another talk earlier, you know,

00:16:57.930 --> 00:16:59.840
there's a typo on this slide:

00:16:59.864 --> 00:17:03.882
but the dilated eyes
from having an eye exam

00:17:03.907 --> 00:17:05.709
when you get those drops in your eyes.

00:17:06.368 --> 00:17:09.646
Another form of migraine
is an aural migraine

00:17:09.671 --> 00:17:13.289
which can cause part or all
of your vision to be obscured.

00:17:14.511 --> 00:17:19.643
Bright sun, either shining
directly on your eyes or on your screen,

00:17:19.668 --> 00:17:24.010
can make it hard to see when
the contrast isn't very different.

00:17:25.168 --> 00:17:29.198
Allergies similar to the
smoke irritant in our scenario

00:17:29.730 --> 00:17:31.242
can cause your eyes to blur

00:17:32.793 --> 00:17:36.575
or maybe something as simple as you
forgot your reading glasses.

00:17:37.623 --> 00:17:40.934
Visual accessibility benefits everyone.

00:17:44.490 --> 00:17:47.186
All of these scenarios
are real-life examples,

00:17:47.211 --> 00:17:51.663
many that I have personally experienced
or know somebody who has.

00:17:52.337 --> 00:17:54.742
Maybe you can relate to one or two of them.

00:17:54.767 --> 00:17:56.938
Maybe you can relate to a lot of them.

00:17:57.740 --> 00:18:01.646
Either way, I challenge you to
come up with your own examples

00:18:01.679 --> 00:18:03.543
that you can share with others

00:18:03.567 --> 00:18:07.753
that will help accessibility considerations
become more commonplace.

00:18:08.468 --> 00:18:12.110
And at the very least,
I hope I have convinced you

00:18:12.135 --> 00:18:17.085
that making your website accessible
makes it better for everyone.

00:18:19.093 --> 00:18:20.490
Thank you for listening.

00:18:21.672 --> 00:18:25.061
You can find me on Twitter,
send me an email,

00:18:25.086 --> 00:18:28.785
and of course, gratuitous plug
for my podcast, wp_contribute()

00:18:28.810 --> 00:18:31.604
on all of the podcast players.

00:18:33.609 --> 00:18:35.617
<v Mike> Well, that was a great talk.

00:18:36.974 --> 00:18:42.643
Thank you so much for
taking the time to share that.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:47.058
We are waiting for some
questions to come in,

00:18:47.091 --> 00:18:50.595
so if you have any questions,
please put them into the YouTube channel

00:18:50.620 --> 00:18:53.565
and then they'll be
brought over to the webpage

00:18:53.598 --> 00:18:56.086
at wpaccessibilityday.org.

00:18:56.111 --> 00:18:58.910
And you can actually
find Christina's slides

00:18:58.935 --> 00:19:01.239
at our website as well.

00:19:01.272 --> 00:19:08.838
But as we're waiting
for those questions to come in,

00:19:08.863 --> 00:19:10.883
and we do have one,

00:19:10.907 --> 00:19:16.679
I had a-- something that
reminded me from your talk is

00:19:17.115 --> 00:19:20.406
I was listening to someone
from Interactive Accessibility,

00:19:20.431 --> 00:19:24.294
and they said something that
when designers are put in a box,

00:19:24.319 --> 00:19:25.765
they become more creative.

00:19:26.205 --> 00:19:29.142
And I think that's very true.

00:19:29.167 --> 00:19:32.549
And again, this was a while ago
before accessibility was common,

00:19:32.574 --> 00:19:36.221
but your point of, yes, you
can still design pretty things,

00:19:36.246 --> 00:19:39.958
you can still make
interactive applications,

00:19:39.983 --> 00:19:42.672
but it doesn't mean that
you're being restricted

00:19:42.697 --> 00:19:44.386
because of accessibility.

00:19:44.849 --> 00:19:46.508
<v Christina> Exactly, and that--

00:19:46.533 --> 00:19:50.999
I mean, I've learned something like
that too, that sometimes we need the box

00:19:51.556 --> 00:19:53.499
to be more creative, right?

00:19:54.888 --> 00:19:57.573
The more you know about
the box that you're in,

00:19:57.598 --> 00:19:59.279
the more creative you can get.

00:19:59.557 --> 00:20:01.835
So absolutely, it helps.

00:20:02.287 --> 00:20:05.220
<v Mike> Cool, we're going to
some questions. Our first question is,

00:20:05.245 --> 00:20:09.082
"For businesses,
what is the easiest fix or win

00:20:09.107 --> 00:20:11.737
for making an e-commerce
site more accessible?"

00:20:13.118 --> 00:20:14.705
<v Christina> That's a good question.

00:20:15.713 --> 00:20:21.184
I mean, ultimately, it depends on
how accessible your site already is.

00:20:22.148 --> 00:20:26.872
But one of the biggest things
that I think a lot of people miss out on

00:20:26.897 --> 00:20:28.971
when considering accessibility,

00:20:28.996 --> 00:20:31.955
sort of just trying to do
these quick and easy fixes,

00:20:32.344 --> 00:20:35.076
is focusing on those contact forms,

00:20:35.101 --> 00:20:38.014
making sure that you can back tab in them,

00:20:38.038 --> 00:20:40.958
that you can get into them
with the mouse or with the keyboard

00:20:40.982 --> 00:20:46.938
or with the screen reader or however
somebody might need to access your form,

00:20:46.963 --> 00:20:49.233
making sure that they can get into it,

00:20:49.257 --> 00:20:51.550
they can move around in it,

00:20:52.677 --> 00:20:57.304
they know always what the fields are
that they're typing into,

00:20:57.486 --> 00:21:00.434
and that it's easy for them to submit.

00:21:02.860 --> 00:21:05.894
<v Mike> Okay, our next question is,

00:21:05.919 --> 00:21:09.066
"Do you have suggestions
for tools people can use

00:21:09.090 --> 00:21:13.948
to stop or block annoying
autoplaying sound and video?"

00:21:13.973 --> 00:21:16.643
<v Christina> Oh, that's an awesome question.

00:21:17.254 --> 00:21:22.054
I do not, but now, I didn't even think
to look for something like that

00:21:22.079 --> 00:21:24.040
because literally, I wasn't joking.

00:21:24.065 --> 00:21:27.752
I update sites every week
as part of my job,

00:21:27.785 --> 00:21:31.046
and there's one site that
has a video that autoplays,

00:21:31.071 --> 00:21:33.330
and it's really far down on the screen too.

00:21:33.355 --> 00:21:37.050
And every single week, it scares me.

00:21:37.075 --> 00:21:38.193
Every single week.

00:21:38.811 --> 00:21:41.463
So I am going to look into that

00:21:41.488 --> 00:21:45.248
and see if I can find something
that I'm going to use,

00:21:45.273 --> 00:21:49.207
and then I'll update the answer
on the website when I do.

00:21:50.808 --> 00:21:55.246
<v Mike> Excellent; so on a
similar vein, 'cause, you know,

00:21:55.279 --> 00:21:59.378
some people are, you know, we're on a
WordPress, you know, Accessibility Day,

00:21:59.403 --> 00:22:02.120
so obviously, we're making our
WordPress sites accessible,

00:22:02.153 --> 00:22:05.256
but not everybody
uses the WordPress CMS.

00:22:05.289 --> 00:22:07.292
Do you think any of the
out-of-the-box,

00:22:07.317 --> 00:22:09.696
like turnkey solutions
that do work with WordPress

00:22:09.721 --> 00:22:12.430
but also things like
Shopify or Wix or Weebly,

00:22:12.463 --> 00:22:14.234
like AudioEye or any of those,

00:22:14.259 --> 00:22:17.972
ayou know, pplication SAS
accessibility services,

00:22:18.568 --> 00:22:19.731
have any value,

00:22:19.755 --> 00:22:24.062
or do you think the site
should just be natively accessible

00:22:24.087 --> 00:22:26.711
from the beginning of the design process?

00:22:26.744 --> 00:22:30.344
<v Christina> I mean, I do believe the
more natively accessible it is, the better.

00:22:32.400 --> 00:22:33.985
Starting with that foundation,

00:22:34.009 --> 00:22:37.273
you know, when--again, people
talk about how much it costs

00:22:37.298 --> 00:22:38.806
to make a site accessible,

00:22:38.831 --> 00:22:41.559
it's actually one of those
retrofitting issues, right?

00:22:41.592 --> 00:22:47.167
It's more costly to retrofit
accessibility into your existing site

00:22:47.192 --> 00:22:50.835
than to build it from the
beginning with accessibility.

00:22:50.868 --> 00:22:55.444
And when you--lots of those things
regarding accessibility

00:22:55.469 --> 00:22:58.801
don't even have anything to
do with the platform you're on,

00:22:58.826 --> 00:23:02.480
you know, things like the contrasts
of the colors that you use.

00:23:02.513 --> 00:23:05.483
Those are design choices that
need to be made from the beginning.

00:23:05.516 --> 00:23:11.068
So anything and everything you can do
to start from a good place of accessibility

00:23:11.093 --> 00:23:12.553
from the very beginning

00:23:12.590 --> 00:23:13.846
is the best way to go.

00:23:15.497 --> 00:23:17.068
<v Mike> Okay, excellent.

00:23:17.141 --> 00:23:19.664
So I'm not seeing any other questions,

00:23:19.697 --> 00:23:23.835
so I think we are
going to wrap it up.

00:23:23.868 --> 00:23:25.700
Again, thank you so much, Christina,

00:23:25.725 --> 00:23:30.183
for taking the time and
sharing your expertise with us.

00:23:31.350 --> 00:23:35.096
And your slides can be found
at wpaccessibilityday.org,

00:23:35.121 --> 00:23:36.771
and you're also on Twitter, right?

00:23:36.814 --> 00:23:38.390
<v Christina> I am on Twitter, yes.

00:23:38.415 --> 00:23:41.172
<v Mike> Okay, and what's your username?

00:23:41.197 --> 00:23:44.013
<v Christina> Twitter username is amethystanswers.

00:23:44.046 --> 00:23:47.575
I will spell that because very few
people know how to spell amethyst.

00:23:47.988 --> 00:23:56.470
So that is
A-M-E-T-H-Y-S-T A-N-S-W-E-R-S.

00:23:57.594 --> 00:23:59.300
<v Mike> Excellent;
and while you're on Twitter,

